<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-standard-forms">
    <title>Standard forms: minterms and maxterms</title>
    <shorttitle>Standard forms</shorttitle>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            In this section we will introduce two standard forms for Boolean
            functions: the <term>minterm</term> and the <term>maxterm</term>.
            Every boolean function can be represented as a sum of minterms or
            as a product of maxterms. Each of these representations leads
            directly to a circuit.
        </p>
        <p>
            Consider the expression <me>
                \bar{x} y z + x \bar{y} z
            </me>.
            If we list out the barred and unbarred versions of all the
            variables that appear in the expression, we get the following:
            <me>
                x, \bar{x}, y, \bar{y}, z, \bar{z}
            </me>.
            These occur in complementary pairs: for any choice of logical
            values of <m>x</m>, <m>y</m>, <m>z</m>, exactly one of the
            members of each pair is 1 and the other is 0. The table
            summarizes the situation.
        </p>
        <table>
            <title>Values of the literals</title>
            <tabular halign="center">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>minterm</cell>
                    <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>z</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>m_0 = \bar{x} \bar{y} \bar{z}</m></cell>
                    <cell>0</cell>
                    <cell>0</cell>
                    <cell>0</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>m_1 = \bar{x} \bar{y} z</m></cell>
                    <cell>0</cell>
                    <cell>0</cell>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>m_2 = \bar{x} y \bar{z}</m></cell>
                    <cell>0</cell>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                    <cell>0</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>m_3 = \bar{x} y z</m></cell>
                    <cell>0</cell>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>m_4 = x \bar{y} \bar{z}</m></cell>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                    <cell>0</cell>
                    <cell>0</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>m_5 = x \bar{y} z</m></cell>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                    <cell>0</cell>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>m_6 = x y \bar{z}</m></cell>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                    <cell>0</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>m_7 = x y z</m></cell>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </introduction>
</section>